---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navbar from '@/components/Navbar';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout title="Design Patterns - Web Interfaces">
  <Navbar client:idle />
  
  <main class="lg:ml-64 min-h-screen bg-white">
    <!-- Header -->
    <section class="px-6 lg:px-16 pt-20 lg:pt-16 pb-12 lg:pb-16 border-b border-gray-200">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <a 
          href="/" 
          class="inline-block text-[14px] text-[#9ca3af] hover:text-black underline transition-colors mb-6"
        >
          Back
        </a>
        <h1 class="main-text text-black mb-4">
          Design Patterns
        </h1>
        <p class="text-lg lg:text-xl text-gray-600">
          Proven solutions to common design problems in web interfaces.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <section class="px-6 lg:px-16 py-12 lg:py-16">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-2xl lg:text-3xl font-semibold text-black mb-6">Understanding Design Patterns</h2>
        <p class="text-base lg:text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Design patterns are reusable solutions to common problems. They represent best practices that have evolved 
          through years of user research, testing, and iteration. By understanding and applying these patterns, 
          you can create interfaces that feel familiar and intuitive to users.
        </p>
        <p class="text-base lg:text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
          Patterns aren't rigid rulesâ€”they're starting points that can be adapted to fit your specific context 
          and user needs. The key is understanding why patterns work before deciding when and how to apply them.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Divider -->
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-16">
      <div class="border-t border-gray-200"></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Common Patterns -->
    <section class="px-6 lg:px-16 py-12 lg:py-16">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-2xl lg:text-3xl font-semibold text-black mb-8">Essential Patterns</h2>
        
        <div class="space-y-10">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-black mb-3">1. Navigation Patterns</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              From hamburger menus to mega menus, navigation patterns help users move through your site. 
              Learn when to use persistent navigation, breadcrumbs, tabs, and other wayfinding solutions.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-black mb-3">2. Form Patterns</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              Effective form design reduces friction and increases completion rates. Explore patterns for input 
              fields, validation, error handling, multi-step forms, and progressive disclosure.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-black mb-3">3. Content Patterns</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              How you organize and present content impacts engagement and comprehension. Study card layouts, 
              masonry grids, list views, and other content organization patterns.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-black mb-3">4. Feedback Patterns</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              Users need to know what's happening. Examine patterns for loading states, progress indicators, 
              success messages, error handling, and system feedback.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-black mb-3">5. Search Patterns</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              From simple search boxes to advanced filtering interfaces, search patterns help users find what 
              they need. Learn about autocomplete, filters, faceted search, and results presentation.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-black mb-3">6. Onboarding Patterns</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              First impressions matter. Explore patterns for introducing features, guiding new users, and 
              creating effective tutorials without overwhelming people.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Divider -->
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-16">
      <div class="border-t border-gray-200"></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Implementation Guidelines -->
    <section class="px-6 lg:px-16 py-12 lg:py-16">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-2xl lg:text-3xl font-semibold text-black mb-8">Using Patterns Effectively</h2>
        
        <div class="space-y-8">
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-black mb-2">Understand Context</h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              A pattern that works in one context may not work in another. Consider your users, their goals, 
              and the specific problem you're solving.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-black mb-2">Don't Blindly Copy</h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              Understanding why a pattern works is more important than copying it exactly. Adapt patterns 
              to fit your unique requirements.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-black mb-2">Test with Users</h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              Even proven patterns should be validated with your specific audience. User testing reveals 
              whether a pattern actually solves your users' problems.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-black mb-2">Document Your Decisions</h4>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              When you implement a pattern, document why you chose it and how it should be used. 
              This creates consistency and helps teams make aligned decisions.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  /* Main text - responsive sizing */
  .main-text {
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 28px;
  }

  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .main-text {
      font-size: 42px;
      line-height: 44px;
    }
  }
</style>
